I thought this recipe had great potential given the ingredients,but it was a big disappointment. Way too dry. I have artichoke dip recipes that are much better than this

Rating: 3
My family and I really enjoyed this dip, but I had to make some substitutions - I used 1 can of artichoke hearts and two small cans of water chestnuts, chopped. I had no jalapenos so I used red pepper flakes. No onions in the house, so I used the ole standbye envelope of french onion soup. Ultimately, not really the same dip at all, I guess!

Rating: 3
Have made this twice already and am making it again for Christmas Eve! It is very tasty and easy to make. Be sure the jalapeno you use is spicy (taste it before you cut it -- some are so mild you'd think you were eating a sweet bell pepper). You might need to add more red pepper sauce if the jalapeno is mild. I also found it tasted better only slightly warm as opposed to hot from the oven.

Rating: 3
My company loved this appetizer before thanksgiving dinner.

Rating: 4
LOVED this recipe! Made just half of it for my family (7 of us with inlaws and "outlaws") and it was the first thing to go. I omitted the jalapenos (I'm allergic) and substituted a tablespoon of minced dried onion for the green onions, as mine had spoiled in the crisper. I also used 2 jars of marinated artichoke hearts, and that may be what the previous cooks need (more of this) to kick up the taste. Increased the mozzarella as well, for volume. EVERYONE left with the recipe.

Rating: 2
I agree with the reviewer that gave it 1 fork---it certainly does not bubble or brown. I think the recipe calls for too much cream cheese. I might cut down on the cream cheese next time and add more mayo. My guests liked it, but it certainly was not one of the best dips I have ever made. Needs salt and something else to zing it up. It certainly has good ingredients. It has the potential to be very good, but something is missing.....

Rating: 1
I made this last night to bring to a cocktail party. I thought this dip was a just ok and certainly not that eye catching...there are a lot of great ingredients that somehow never quite come together. I increased the jalepeno and it still was blah. Not sure about the browned and bubbly part either...this was just the great white mess! The best part about this dip was the pita chips....which guests used to scoop up other dip offerings.

Rating: 4
This is the best artichoke dip I've ever made. I really liked it with the pita chips, too, although 20 minutes is WAY too long to bake the chips--they were blackened after 15 minutes! I would suggest checking them for doneness after 8-10 minutes. The recipe makes a lot of dip, so unless you're making it for a big party, I would suggest cutting it in half.